04773nam a22007095i 9780231530873DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20122012nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2012006493  a97802315308737 a10.7312/rowl158542doi  a(DE-B1597)459283  a(OCoLC)979969537  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aDS872.N35bR68 2013 4aDS872.N35bR68 2013 7aHIS0210002bisacsh04a952/.025092aB2231 aRowley, G., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut13aAn Imperial Concubine's Tale :bScandal, Shipwreck, and Salvation in Seventeenth-Century Japan /cG. Rowley. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2012] 4c©2012  a1 online resource (280 p.) :b‹B›11 color illus, 3 maps, 1 chart‹/B›  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tPreface and Acknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tChapter 1. A Courtier’s Life, in and out of the World -- tChapter 2. The Year 1600: A World Again at War -- tChapter 3. At the Court of the Dragon -- tChapter 4. Scandal -- tChapter 5. The Tale of Kazan -- tChapter 6. Shipwreck -- tChapter 7. The Long Reprieve -- tChapter 8 Salvation -- tEpilogue -- tPrincipal Characters -- tGlossary -- tAbbreviations -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aJapan in the early seventeenth century was a wild place. Serial killers stalked the streets of Kyoto at night, while noblemen and women mingled freely at the imperial palace, drinking saké and watching kabuki dancing in the presence of the emperor's principal consort. Among these noblewomen was an imperial concubine named Nakanoin Nakako, who in 1609 became embroiled in a sex scandal involving both courtiers and young women in the emperor's service. As punishment, Nakako was banished to an island in the Pacific Ocean, but she never reached her destination. Instead, she was shipwrecked and spent fourteen years in a remote village on the Izu Peninsula before she was finally allowed to return to Kyoto. In 1641, Nakako began a new adventure: she entered a convent and became a Buddhist nun.Recounting the remarkable story of this resilient woman and her war-torn world, G. G. Rowley investigates aristocratic family archives, village storehouses, and the records of imperial convents. She follows the banished concubine as she endures rural exile, receives an unexpected reprieve, and rediscovers herself as the abbess of a nunnery. While unraveling Nakako's unusual tale, Rowley also reveals the little-known lives of samurai women who sacrificed themselves on the fringes of the great battles that brought an end to more than a century of civil war. Written with keen insight and genuine affection, An Imperial Concubine's Tale tells the true story of a woman's extraordinary life in seventeenth-century Japan.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aBuddhist nunszJapanvBiography. 0aConcubinagezJapanxHistoryy17th century. 7aHISTORY / Asia / Japan.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagez978311064977208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044247240uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/rowl1585440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231530873423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780231530873/original  a978-3-11-044247-2  Columbia University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-064977-2  Asian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagec2000d2014  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV